Introduction:

We will cluster equities that move together using unsupervised methods, build regression-based hedge ratios to capture mean-reverting spreads, and use supervised models such as Gradient Boosting Decision Trees to predict stock movement into earnings. The dataset we will be utilizing is the NYSE Trade and Quote (TAQ) provided by Wharton Research and Data Services. This dataset provides intraday records of all trades and quotes for all US equities in the National Market System, including all stocks listed in the NYSE, AMEX, and Nasdaq. We will be using the Daily Product Coverage. It offers dates from 2003-present, as opposed to Monthly Product Coverage from 1993-2014. The fields within this dataset that are directly relevant to our project are trade price and volume, bid/ask quotes and sizes, timestamps, and ticker identifiers.

Dataset Link:   
[https://wrds-www.wharton.upenn.edu/pages/about/data-vendors/nyse-trade-and-quote-taq/](https://wrds-www.wharton.upenn.edu/pages/about/data-vendors/nyse-trade-and-quote-taq/) 

Background

Earnings announcements are official public statements of a company's profitability over a time period and stand as one of the most important scheduled events in equity markets. With common increases in volatility and trading volume, holding a stock during earnings announcements can result in significant exposure to risk if price swings occur. We will cluster equities that move together using unsupervised methods, build regression-based hedge ratios to capture mean-reverting spreads, and use supervised models such as SVM and Gradient Boosting Decision Trees to predict stock movement into earnings.   
   
Prior research supports our use of these methods. Avellaneda and Lee (2010) show that "PCA of the correlation matrix for the broad equity market in the US gives rise to risk-factors that have economic significance because they can be interpreted as long–short portfolios of industry sectors", supporting our approach of clustering equities on correlation to capture equities that move together. Furthermore, their study shows hedge ratios derived from regression can provide mean-reverting spreads, giving us a good basis for how we can conduct analysis on potential future risk.   
   
Lastly, as we use supervised models to predict stock movement, Huang, Nakamori, and Wang (2005) state that "SVM is a promising type of tool for financial forecasting" and, through an empirical analysis, found that "SVM is superior to the other individual classification methods in forecasting weekly movement direction of NIKKEI 225 Index", solidifying SVM as strong candidate for predicting stock movement around earnings reports. Moreover, “in economics, decisions are often based on forecasts of directional up or downward movements of the variable of interest,” emphasizing the importance of models that provide not just accuracy but strong predictive direction for trading decisions (Blaskowitz & Herwartz, 2011). Overall, through reviewing relevant literature we have found evidence that our intended methods will provide real economic meaning to mitigate risk in the equities held by retail investors around earnings reports. 

Problem Definition:

The problem we are trying to solve is that, as retail investors, by holding a stock, we are exposed to risk around earnings reporting whether our stock goes up or down. Our plan is to determine a strategy to mitigate these risks. So, our strategy has three parts. First, we want to use unsupervised learning to categorize equities into clusters that move together. Then, we want to use linear regression to find hedge ratios between those equities. Finally, we want to use SVM or Gradient Boosting Decision Trees to make predictions on the direction of stocks going into those earning reports.

Motivation

The motivation for this project revolves around the fact that retail investors do not have the same accessibility to statistical models and machine learning methods as hedge funds or other large institutions do. Our goal is to decrease this gap by providing retail investors an approach to reduce downside exposure through several machine learning methods we will utilize in this project.

Methods:

**Data Processing:**

*Qualitative Data for Clustering*  
We utilized two datasets in order to retrieve qualitative data on all S\&P 500 companies, the desired fields being: sector, net income, sales, market value, head quarters, and ticker.

We began by downloading a dataset of North American companies from Wharton’s Compustat database containing company financial fundamentals. In order to filter our initial dataset to only S\&P 500 companies, we downloaded a separate CSV of all current S\&P 500 tickers.

All qualitative data preprocessing was performed in Python using pandas. The key steps and methods usedwere:

**1\. Dropping Unnecessary Data Columns**  
We removed several data columns that would not contribute meaningful information to our model and so were not our target fields.  
This step removed noise and retained only the relevant fields.

**2\. Date and Year Parsing**  
The “datadate” column for the fiscal reporting date was found to have multiple formats throughout the dataset, such as YYYYMMDD or YYYY/MM/DD, so we parsed these entries into a standardized format of YYYY-MM-DD. We then created a consistent “year” column, taking the year from either one of our existing columns like “fyear”, “year”, or “fiscalyear” and otherwise taking it from the parsed “datadate”. Finally, we removed any fields with a date greater than 2025 to ensure the data is reliable.

**3\. Deduplication**  
Since Compustat can have multiple rows per company, either for different years or different security issues, and we want to have one row per company, we needed one identifier to solidify the entry to use. The “gvkey” (Compustat’s global company identifier) and “iid” (Issue Identifier) identifies different securities. Together, this allowed us to create unique groups. We then sorted the data and kept only the latest row per firm/issue.

**4\. Column Renaming**  
For clarity, we renamed all our relevant fields to:

sector  
net\_income  
sales  
market\_value  
company\_HQ  
ticker

**5\. Ticker Standardization**  
We aligned the ticker formats in both datasets, cleaning them by converting to a string, trimming whitespace, making them uppercased and removing special characters.

**6\. Filtering to S\&P 500 Companies**  
We used the tickers as a primary key to keep only the Compustat rows whose cleaned tickers were found in the S\&P 500 dataset, filtering the dataset to only firms currently listed in the S\&P 500\.

**7\. Market Cap Normalization**  
Lastly, we normalized the market value column in “clustering.ipynb” since large companies, like Apple, have market caps orders of magnitude above smaller ones, and also so that features of different scales contribute equally to clustering since clustering is distance-based. In order to do so, we applied a log transformation to compress the large range and used min-max scaling to rescale the values between 0 and 1\.

*Qualitative Data*

For the quantitative side of the preprocessing, we downloaded the daily price data including high, low, close for each S\&P stock. Then, for each trading day we calculated the maximum intraday deviation from the previous close in order to show how a stock was volatile over time. Running Principal Component Analysis on these daily returns allowed us to create features that best represented the relation between stocks’ movements. We took used log ratios of our features where applicable to ensure that upside and downside moves were measured the same in our model, and that data was on a consistent scale across all tickers.

**ML Algorithms**

*Gaussian Mixture Model*  
We used the Gaussian mixture model as our main method of soft-clustering to cluster S\&P stocks that “move together”. This model assumes that data points are created from a “mixture” of gaussian distributions and this allows for probabilistic assignments of clusters allowing our stocks to be able to be within multiple clusters.

We chose GMM for multiple reasons and compared it with a baseline of KMeans with 10 clusters. We found GMM dominates for our project for these reasons:

**1\. Volatility of Financial Data**  
Due to working with financial, time series data we deal with a high variance of values. The GMM allows for clusters of different shapes/orientations allowing for a more suitable algorithm compared to fixed KMeans clusters.

**2\. Overlapping Clusters**  
With financial data and the features we compute, stocks will have a lot of overlapping features which can cause problems during clustering as the assignments can be messy. Using soft clustering with GMM, we allow much more interpretable measurements.

We first initialized our GMM with 10 clusters and then in order to estimate the parameters for our GMM, we used the expectation maximization algorithm and fit the model according to 122 features for each stock (100 time series volatility components, 11 one hot encoded sectors identifier, 9 one hot encoded company locations, and the log transform of sales, net income, and market cap.) In order to find the optimal number of clusters, we also used Bayesian Information Criterion and Akaike Information Criterion. This allowed us to determine the number of components that explain the data without overfitting by performing GMM on a component count range from 1-29 and finding the best fit. We also implemented a similar model using KMeans rather than GMM in order to compare the differences between using a fixed-size and hard clustering compared to a variable-size and soft-clustering. However, we determined that with the existence of highly volatile stock data, GMM is the way to go.

*Ridge Regression*  
Once clusters were set using GMM, we wanted to quantify the relationships between stocks within the same cluster. The goal of this model is to predict returns using Ridge Regression with an optimal regularization per stock. The coefficients from that prediction are our hedge ratios (giving us quantitative reasoning on how much each stock is going to move based on its correlated stocks movement) and the optimal combination of stocks within the same cluster to hedge our target stock. These ratios allow us to create pairs or baskets for mean-reverting spreads to help reduce risk around earnings reports.

We estimated hedge ratios for each stock by getting the daily returns using the returns of the other stocks within the same cluster as features. We used the following data sources from preprocessing:  
Clustered.pkl: assigning each stock to a soft cluster from the GMM output.  
Daily\_data.pkl: containing daily high, low, and close price history for all S\&P 500 stocks.  
From this we computed daily returns, which served as our time-series features.

Financial time-series data is highly noisy and can be highly correlated across equities, especially those within similar sectors. We use Ridge Regression as opposed to Least Squares Regression because Least Squares Regression would likely overfit our data. On the other hand, Ridge Regression introduces an L2 penalty that reduces variance and stabilizes the model by shrinking coefficients. This generalizes better for more reliable hedge ratios.

We performed time-series cross-validation to find the most optimal regularization strength (alpha) for each stock. This helps us select the optimal amount of shrinkage to keep the model stable and still capture the relationships within each cluster.

Overall, our clustering tells us roughly which stocks are supposed to move together using general qualitative data. Finding hedge ratios using regression takes this a step further by giving more definitive, quantitative reasoning on how much each stock is going to move based on its correlated stocks movement. This is necessary for actually determining sizing and direction of trades.

Gradient Boosting Decision Trees  
We aimed to use Gradient Boosting Decision Trees for earnings stock price prediction. We figured Gradient Boosting would be a good choice because we had a very large feature space, as well as because we wanted to attempt to encompass the nonlinear relationships within our data while also maintaining some degree of interpretability using the feature importances output by XGBoost.

We began by using our clusters to build a list of the top 10 most correlated stocks with each of our tickers. From there, we compiled various time-series statistics, such as price momentum, volatility, and volume ratios for each of our correlated stocks. Then we also added other statistics such as expert predictions on Earnings Per Share to our feature set.

Since we had such a large feature set, we had a large amount of invalid values, and we had to mitigate these by analyzing the column and filling with the feature that would make the most sense. Gradient boosting has 7 key hyperparameters:  number of estimators, representing the number of trees, max\_depth, representing the max depth of each tree, learning rate, representing the rate at which the gradient descent algorithm learns, row/column subsample, representing the number of rows or features seen by each tree, and alpha/beta, which are the L1 and L2 penalties placed onto weights in the tree. Due to the noisy nature of stock data, subsampling and regularization are very important for preventing over fitting.

Finally, our model gives us a general idea as to the move of a stock going into earnings. This coupled with the hedge ratios can give us a useful tool for mitigating short term event driven market risks.

Results and Discussion:

![][image2]  
These are visualizations of our Silhouette and ARI scores using different numbers of clusters. Using these graphs, we can select a number of clusters that balances the inverse shape of these scores, while also creating a clustering that gives us meaningful insight (e.g there is no point in choosing 1 or 2 clusters just because they have a high silhouette score since it doesn't actually help our goal). We have decided to go with 8 clusters. It is worth noting that even though our scores aren’t great, it would be hard to do better since stock data is inherently very noisy, and most financial models look for even small advantages in the market. Thus, we are going to move on to our next model of regression and not spend more time trying to improve our clustering.

![][image3]  
This is a visualization of our actual vs predicted returns of our best cluster after performing our ridge regression model 2\. As seen by the graph, the results of this model seem to be the best out of the 3, since the predicted returns very closely mirror the actual returns. Initially, we looked at other forms of regression but ended up with ridge regression since it fundamentally seemed to make the most sense for a financial model. Retroactively looking at the results, this was a good decision. Next steps for this model could include figuring out why performance varies across clusters, and making sure we are preventing overfitting by running this model across a larger time span. To do this, we would first need access to a larger dataset with a longer time period.

![][image4]

Since we have over 100 features, I decided to only include a couple visualizations of our target variable. As the above graphs show, a lot of our features weren’t highly correlated with the target variable in either direction, and this was reflected in our training. We ended up with an R^2 of 0.03, which isn’t a strong correlation at all, but given the difficulty of this regression task, this was actually better than expected. I would also say that we used GridSearchCV to find hyperparameters, but we also focused on using hyperparameters that reduced overfitting primarily, as we didn’t have too large of a dataset, and it was very difficult to compile our features. To improve this model, we would need access to a lot more data, such as options data that we struggled to reliably find, as well as more accurate data, as we found that a lot of the data we found early on wasn’t correct. Additionally, earnings prediction models tend to have generally weaker R^2 values because a plethora of factors play into earnings moves, including more qualitative data such as retail sentiment, which can sometimes not be easily quantified.

Comparison:  
It is hard to compare the results of our 3 models, since they fundamentally complete different tasks and are joined together to achieve our overall goal, instead of having 3 different models completing the same task and comparing which one accomplishes it the best. We can say that, for example, model 2 has the best results since it has a good RMSE value compared to not as great metrics for model 1 and 3, but it is also worth considering that model 2 benefits from model 1 serving as almost a “preprocessing” model, since the outputs from model 1 are used to make model 2 more efficient. In addition, model 3 serves an entirely different purpose as the first two models, and expands on the features provided in model one in an attempt to provide yet another real world use case for our project with the inclusion of earnings predictions.

Next Steps:  
Next Steps would likely revolve around integrating more advanced machine learning techniques and potentially deep learning techniques to hopefully improve the R^2 value obtained in model 3\. While the results for model three were promising considering the difficulty of the tasks and all of the unknown variables, a similar model with a stronger R^2 could potentially be used for a plethora of strategies within the Quantitative Finance industry.

Another potential direction is the development of a fourth model that combines results from models two and three to construct pre-earnings portfolios designed to exploit statistical arbitrage opportunities. Since model one clusters securities, model two estimates hedge ratios, and model three forecasts earnings-related price movements, the natural next step would be a unified framework that ingests a universe of tickers and outputs a portfolio optimized for each earnings season, dynamically adjusting position sizes based on the results provided from models two and three.
